  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">*Brief entry*</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The reference-spectrum expansion of Bethe, Brandow and Petschek is used to express the nuclear reaction matrix as a perturbation series in terms of a state-independent reference matrix. A simple treatment of the projection (or Pauli) operator in the intermediate-state sum is obtained, in the harmonic-oscillator representation of shell-model states by making certain well-defined averages. The same operator is also examined from the point of view that they are made up of localized operators of the nuclear-matter type corresponding to local effective densities which are position-dependent. These two distinct points of view, called respectively global and local, are investigated numerically in the 1 S 0 , 3 S 1 and other states for the Hamada-Johnston potential in an A = 18 nucleus. It is found that the simple local-density approximation for treating the Pauli operator gives results very close to the global treatment, which is considered exact here. In particular, the local approximation reproduces the global results if the position-dependent effective density is allowed to extend, by some 0.9 fm, beyond the local density at the half-density point. By using state-dependent average effective Fermi momenta based on such density distributions, it is shown that the calculation of nuclear reaction matrix elements is now made as simple (and probably as accurate) as that for nuclear matter. The reliable calculation methods thus obtained make it possible to examine the properties of these matrix elements. It is found that the local interactions (in local treatments) are enhanced in the nuclear surface region and that the reduced matrix elements are particularly sensitive to the single-particle energies of the initial state. The 3 S 1 matrix elements are shown to decrease rapidly in strength as the amount of tensor force in the nucleon-nucleon potential increases. The importance of using correct single-particle wave functions is emphasized by showing that in light nuclei improvement of the simple harmonic-oscillator shell model leads to drastic corrections.</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">Elsevier</subfield>
  </datafield>
